									<p><br>The Nine Dragon Wall stands along Cermak and Wentworth in Chinatown. The wall is one of the first landmarks visitors arriving from the red line station see when exiting the station. It prominently features nine large dragons, with over 500 smaller dragons throughout the work. The intricate design is very important in chinese culture. The dragons are red, blue, and gold to symbolize successfulness and good fortune. The number nine symbolizes longevity, eternity, and completeness in Chinese culture.<br> <br />
									The wall stands across from the Dan Ryan Expressway that goes through Chinatown, and is thought to improve the fun schwei from the traffic and congestion. The wall tiles were originally made in China, and assembled in Chicago’s Chinatown. The Chinatown Chamber of Commerce dedicated the Nine Dragon Wall following its completion in 2003.</p>
